  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Emerged from anti-organized crime efforts in the 1920s-1930s\n- Initially focused on combating criminal proceeds from Prohibition-era activities\n- US Treasury used tax laws to prosecute criminals like Al Capone\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970)\n- First comprehensive US legislation targeting financial crimes\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Created reporting requirements to track potentially suspicious financial activities\n\n3. International Development\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global issue\n- FATF (Financial Action Task Force) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US Bank Secrecy Act amendments (1992)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced international cooperation and information sharing\n\n5. Modern Regulatory Framework\n- Comprehensive global regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements\n- Sophisticated technological monitoring systems\n- Significant criminal and civil penalties for violations\n\nThese developments reflect an evolving legal approach to combating financial crimes.",
